A marriage is voidable under Section 12 of the Hindu Marriage Act, 1955 (HMA) on several grounds, including: 

1. if the marriage was performed without the consent of the respondent, or if the consent was obtained by force, coercion, or fraud (Section 12(1)(a) HMA); 
2. if the respondent was suffering from a mental disorder or was subject to recurrent attacks of insanity or epilepsy at the time of the marriage (Section 12(1)(b) HMA); 
3. if the respondent had a communicable venereal disease at the time of the marriage (Section 12(1)(c) HMA); 
4. if the respondent was pregnant by some other person at the time of the marriage (Section 12(1)(d) HMA); 
5. if the marriage was performed when the respondent was below the age of 18 years in the case of a female and 21 years in the case of a male (Section 12(1)(e) and Prohibition of Child Marriage Act, 2006, read with Section 5(iii) HMA, as amended); 
6. if the parties are not competent to enter into a valid marriage under the Act (Section 12(1)(f) HMA).

